# Architecture Consistency Check Rule

When the user asks for a review or consistency check, lead with findings ordered by severity.

Severity:

- P1: broken traceability or wrong relationship that invalidates the model.
- P2: missing required element, orphan, duplicate, or hierarchy violation.
- P3: naming, clarity, or optional completeness issue.

Check:

- Element names are not empty.
- Elements match the hierarchy expected by their view.
- No orphan architecture elements.
- No duplicate same-name same-type siblings under the same parent.
- Logical structural relations use Composition or Aggregation.
- Logical-to-interface relations use Usage, Dependency, or Realization.
- Code-to-logical mapping uses Manifest.
- Service, MicroService, and Component elements have code Manifest links.
- Build elements use Build From to code.
- Delivery elements contain build outputs using Composition or Aggregation.
- Delivery or executable targets deploy with Deployed To or valid containment.
- Context model has exactly one System.
- Actor and ExternalSystem interact with System through interfaces.
- Runtime models reference or instantiate logical elements rather than creating new ones.

Finding format:

```text
[Severity] Rule: <short rule name>
Evidence: <element/relationship/diagram>
Why it matters: <impact>
Fix: <specific modeling change>
```
